    <h2>Pro Tips for Perfect Green Smoothies</h2>

    <h3>1. Use Frozen Fruit</h3>
    <p>Frozen fruit = thicker, creamier smoothies. Plus it's cheaper and lasts longer. 
    I buy big bags of frozen mango, pineapple, and berries from Costco.</p>

    <h3>2. Start with Spinach (Not Kale)</h3>
    <p>Kale has a stronger flavor. Spinach is mild and blends smooth. Once you're comfortable with spinach, 
    then try kale. Baby steps.</p>

    <h3>3. Blend Liquid + Greens First</h3>
    <p>Put your liquid (almond milk, water, etc.) and greens in the blender first. Blend until smooth. 
    THEN add fruit/protein. This prevents chunks.</p>

    <h3>4. Don't Skimp on Sweetness</h3>
    <p>If your smoothie tastes like grass, add more frozen banana or a date. There's no award for suffering. 
    Make it taste good.</p>

    <h3>5. Add Ice for Texture</h3>
    <p>If your smoothie is too thin, throw in 4-5 ice cubes. Instant milkshake texture.</p>

    <h2>Common Green Smoothie Mistakes</h2>

    <p><strong>❌ Too much kale</strong> - Start with 1 cup max. Work your way up.</p>
    <p><strong>❌ Not enough fruit</strong> - You need sweetness to balance the greens.</p>
    <p><strong>❌ Cheap blender</strong> - A good blender (Vitamix, Ninja, Nutribullet) makes a HUGE difference.</p>
    <p><strong>❌ Room temp ingredients</strong> - Frozen fruit = thick, cold, delicious. Room temp = watery disappointment.</p>
    <p><strong>❌ Giving up after one bad smoothie</strong> - It takes a few tries to find your flavor combo. Keep experimenting!</p>

    <h2>FAQ: Green Smoothies</h2>

    <h3>Q: Can I taste the spinach?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Not if you follow these recipes. The fruit masks it completely. I promise.</p>

    <h3>Q: Will this help me lose weight?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Yes, IF you replace a meal (like breakfast) and don't add it on top of your normal eating. 
    These smoothies are 150-300 calories - way less than most breakfasts.</p>

    <h3>Q: Can I prep these ahead?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Sort of. You can portion out ingredients into freezer bags (greens + fruit). 
    In the morning, dump the bag in the blender, add liquid, blend. Don't pre-blend and store - they separate and get gross.</p>

    <h3>Q: Do I need protein powder?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> No, but it helps if you're using this as a meal replacement. Greek yogurt also adds protein.</p>

    <h3>Q: What blender should I buy?</h3>
    <p><strong>A:</strong> Vitamix is the best (but $$$). Ninja or Nutribullet are good budget options ($50-100). 
    Don't use a $20 blender - it won't blend greens smooth.</p>

    <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Green smoothies don't have to suck.</strong> With the right recipes (like these 5), they can be the 
      best part of your morning. Packed with nutrients, taste amazing, and take 5 minutes to make.
    </p>

    <p>
      Start with the <strong>Green Apple Smoothie</strong> (mildest flavor) or the <strong>Tropical Green</strong> (sweetest). 
      Once you're hooked, try the others.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Your body will thank you.</strong> More energy, better digestion, glowing skin, and maybe even some weight loss. 
      All from drinking something delicious.
    </p>

